Diffing
=======

Your new application uses a custom diffing-algorithm, to transition from one view to the other. This algorithm supports css-transitions and is detailed below.

Transitions
-----------
To allow for transitions, the algorithm attaches classes, namely `in` and `out` to your elements. If an element has the class `out` it should be invisible (ideally via `opacity: 0`, to preserve dimensions). When an element enters the view it is given the class `in`, before being allowed to complete a transition. Once the transition is completed (if no transition happens, this is triggered immediately), the `in` class is removed again. So something like this:

	.in {
		transition: opacity 100ms;
	}

	.out {
		opacity: 0;
		transition: opacity 100ms;
	}

will lead to a smooth fade-in/fade-out transition for entering and exiting elements, as well as those which get replaced.

Definitions
-----------
### Same Element
Elements represent the same thing without being identical. Same element type, same ids, same `diff-id` attribute.
Same elements have to be diffed individually, without needing to be removed/added/replaced.

Right:
* Heading with differing text content
* Container with different children
* Simple class change

Wrong
* Elements representing different instances of the same thing (e.g. two divs for specific pictures)

### Equal Element
Elements are equal in regards to element type, child elements(including positions), attributes and if no children are available, textContent.
The order of classes is not important. The existence of attributes (even if empty) is.
Equal elements do not need to be dealt with in any way.
